commText: SRH have scored 131 and 121 in their two matches so far, while conceding scores of 203 and 127 (16 overs). Two crushing defeats with nothing going right in any department. Lots to ponder over. LSG, meanwhile, have bounced back nicely from their defeat against CSK. And they've done it while leaving Quinton de Kock on the bench, while also missing Mark Wood today due to illness. Such are the resources at their disposal. So that's all we have for now. Thanks for joining in. It's a goodbye from Sagar Chawla on behalf of Saurabh Shankar, Kumar Abhishek Das and Venky.

B0$ Very good day at the office I can say. Both (what he enjoyed more?). Runs, wickets - everything is hard-earned. Everything is special. More right-handers in their lineup - knew I would be bowling four overs. This year I'm in a good headspace. Once you have clarity up there, things fall in places. I'm very process-driven, don't think about results. I took a break from cricket for a few months because I was just playing the white-ball formats, so wanted some time off to work on my bowling. What happened last two-three years was I kept getting wider and wider. Whatever I did in the last 3-4 months - getting taller and getting the ball to turn away, it is all coming out really well. People say I don't turn the ball, so that answers it I guess (Markram wicket). I'm trying to recollect how I played in the first 4-5 years in IPL where I was batting at four for MI. Trying to find that rhythm and consistency. Having the clarity helps. I'm okay with any track. Don't mind if I get a MoM. Want to dedicate this to my wife. She has been a constant support, she is who brings out the best version of myself.

B0$ Yesterday (when did he know how the pitch would play?). We've been here for a couple of weeks now. Knew what we were getting into (nature of the pitch). Even when Jaydev bowled a few cutters, it was gripping. Was a no-brainer to bowl spin early. First instinct when I saw both pitches was that we'll need to bat smartly here. We've adapted well as a batting unit. Each person plays very differently. Just have been a couple of chats with the batting group to help each other out. Good to see the players are going there and putting in the practice.

Good effort from our bowlers, we didn’t give them enough runs to play with but they fought hard. (On the next home game) Different conditions once again, the team has played there already. The Punjab Kings are flying high but Sunday is a chance to pinch them.

B0$ Two wins out of two at home for LSG! And they've both come on very different pitches! Previous one was red soil and had more pace and bounce, and Mark Wood blew the opposition away. The one today was really sluggish with the ball gripping and holding, and LSG showed another dimension in their attack with the spinners bowling beautifully. Krunal Pandya, Ravi Bishnoi and Amit Mishra choked Sunrisers and never let them get away. They restricted them to a total of just 121 to set up the game for the hosts. Sunrisers needed to be right on the money with the ball to make a game of it. But that wasn't the case as there were just too many freebies on offer. And to make things worse, they had a very poor day on the field as well. With this defeat, B1$ Plenty for them to ponder.

The Ekana stadium is where the game will be played tonight. But the last game against Delhi saw plenty of runs being scored. LSG thumped DC to start proceedings in IPL 2023. But they were humbled by CSK a few days later. SRH on the other hand were handed a shellacking by RR in their opening encounter. On arrival in Lucknow, you will see a lot of hoardings that announce 'Muskuraiye, aap Lucknow mein hai (Smile, you're in Lucknow)'. It's an old greeting from the city for its visitors. The Ekana International Stadium, built in 'New' Lucknow isn't as courteous though. The invite to the stadium through hoardings on the white exterior walls, visibly clear even 50 meters away, reads: 'Adab se harayenge (We will thrash you, politely)'. 
 
For cricket, Old Lucknow's tehzeeb makes way for New Lucknow's teekhi zubaan. 
 
The bold wordplay, however, can be daunting for the visiting teams only as long as the KL Rahul-led side put on performances worth the weight of their words. The last time they played at the venue - also their first-ever home game - they outplayed Delhi Capitals with bat, ball on the field. Their next visitors - Sunrisers Hyderabad - were at the receiving end of such a dominant performance, from Rajasthan Royals in their opening match. 
 
But that was on one of the six red-soil tracks where LSG had posted 193. On Friday, the contest will be played on the neighbouring black soil pitch; the one that had come in for heavy criticism after India's narrow win in the low-scoring clash against New Zealand in January. However, since Hardik Pandya's comments that "these wickets are not made for T20s", a lot of work has gone into reviving its state, and it is expected to be in a fairly better condition for run-scoring. 
 
Sunrisers Hyderabad have had a fairly slow start to the tournament, playing only a solitary game in the first week and having a longer time to bond off the field. The lop-sided defeat in the opening encounter notwithstanding, they will be buoyed by the availability of their South African players, Aiden Markram and Marco Jansen, with the former set to make his captaincy debut in the IPL, and hope to find their fix quickly in what is expected to be a busier few weeks from hereon. 
 
For LSG, the South African availability - of Quinton de Kock - may have beefed up their options but also left the team management with a selection problem. Kyle Mayers was shielding their early-season concerns on the batting front: KL Rahul's slow starts followed by the lack of press offered by Deepak Hooda and Krunal Pandya, LSG's No 3 and 4 respectively. With de Kock's return, there is a possible threat to that cushion. 
 
Moreover, there is uncertainty over how the pitch will play. However, with dew expected to play a part, both the captains would be happy to uphold the customs of Old Lucknow at the toss and say 'pehle aap'.
